<paragraph id="4F3B36B7534EFF80FEF3843DFF16FED3" blockId="16.[151,1437,282,705]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Distribution. Arctic (
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FF86843DFDFBFEF7" box="[434,595,318,345]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9934999999999998" metricValueMax="1.9949999999999999" metricValueMin="1.9919999999999998" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="1993.5" valueMax="1995.0" valueMin="1992.0">1992–1995 m</quantity>
), NE Atlantic (
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FCCA843DFC37FEF7" box="[766,927,318,345]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0095" metricValueMax="2.6689999999999996" metricValueMin="1.35" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="2009.5" valueMax="2669.0" valueMin="1350.0">1350–2669 m</quantity>
), E Atlantic (
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FA02843DFB7EFEF7" box="[1078,1238,318,345]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3415" metricValueMax="1.6789999999999998" metricValueMin="1.004" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="1341.5" valueMax="1679.0" valueMin="1004.0">1004–1679 m</quantity>
), SPA (
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FB1E843DFF19FED3" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.31" metricValueMax="1.68" metricValueMin="0.94" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="1310.0" valueMax="1680.0" valueMin="940.0">940–1680 m</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4F3B36B7534EFF80FEF38485FBC7FD6F" blockId="16.[151,1437,282,705]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Remarks. The 
<collectionCode id="2995AE72534EFF80FF448485FE35FE0F" box="[368,413,390,417]" country="Germany" name="Museum Donaueschingen" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">MD</collectionCode>
<specimenCount id="5982FD3E534EFF80FFAA8485FD90FE0E" box="[414,568,390,417]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="generic">50 specimens</specimenCount>
are 6.5–7.0 mm dd, disc pentagonal or slightly indented interradially, with margin covered in small rugose granules and centre with small cylindrical spines with terminal thorns, radial shields raised and rib like with oval distal section exposed (
<figureCitation id="D7BF2A32534EFF80FCC584CDFCE5FE47" box="[753,845,462,489]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
), oral shields trapezoid to hemispherical, two times as wide as long, three to four conical to capitate rugose oral papillae (
<figureCitation id="D7BF2A32534EFF80FDE284F1FB99FDA3" box="[982,1073,498,525]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1894]" captionTargetId="figure-26@18.[151,1436,181,1894]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A) Ophiacantha veterna, MNHN IE.2009.1562, dorsal outline. (B) MNHN IE.2009.1563, ventral view. (C–E) Ophiosabine cuspidata, MNHN IE.2009.1558, C: dorsal outline, D: dorsal view, E: ventral view. (F) Ophiotreta spectabilis, MNHN IE.2009.1564, dorsal view. (G–H) Ophiolimna bairdi, MNHN IE.2009.1571, G: dorsal and H: ventral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404692" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404692/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
), DAPs fan to kite-shaped and separate, to eight arm spines with tiny thorns, upper to three segments long and one tiny spiniform thorny tentacle scale. They are morphologically consistent with material from the North Atlantic including the 
<typeStatus id="903F8815534EFF80FAEB8738FAA7FDFB" box="[1247,1295,571,597]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">type</typeStatus>
description. Although 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534EFF80FF33875CFE10FDD7" author="Paterson, G. L. J." box="[263,440,606,633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref35334" refString="Paterson, G. L. J. (1985) The deep-sea Ophiuroidea of the North Atlantic Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Zoology, 49, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1985">Paterson (1985)</bibRefCitation>
considered this species to be a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534EFF80FD9F875DFA8CFDD7" authority="Verrill, 1885" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1885" box="[939,1316,606,633]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="enopla">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534EFF80FD9F875DFB27FDD6" box="[939,1167,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Ophiacantha enopla</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534EFF80FAA1875DFA8CFDD7" author="Verrill, A. E." box="[1173,1316,606,633]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="149 - 157" refId="ref36586" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1885) Notice of the remarkable marine fauna occupying the outer banks off the southern coast of New England, No. 11. American Journal of Science, 29, 149 - 157. https: // doi. org / 10.2475 / ajs. s 3 - 29.170.149" type="journal article" year="1885">Verrill, 1885</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534EFF80FB1A875CFEDBFD32" author="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M." pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="76 - 111" refId="ref33866" refString="Martynov, A. V. &amp; Litvinova, N. M. (2008) Deep-water Ophiuroidea of the northern Atlantic with descriptions of three new species and taxonomic remarks on certain genera and species. Marine Biology Research, 4, 76 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 17451000701840066" type="journal article" year="2008">Martynov &amp; Litvinova (2008)</bibRefCitation>
re-established 
<taxonomicName id="88844D34534EFF80FC288780FD3AFD32" authorityName="Koehler" authorityYear="1907" box="[540,658,643,669]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Ophiacanthidae" genus="Ophiacantha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ophiacanthida" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="veterna">
<emphasis id="7DF0EAA5534EFF80FC288780FD3AFD32" box="[540,658,643,669]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">O. veterna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a full species. 
<bibRefCitation id="2B154B46534EFF80FD6C8781FBB5FD33" author="Paterson, G. L. J." box="[856,1053,642,669]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref35334" refString="Paterson, G. L. J. (1985) The deep-sea Ophiuroidea of the North Atlantic Ocean. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History) Zoology, 49, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1985">Paterson’s (1985)</bibRefCitation>
record of this species from 
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FB618781FA35FD33" box="[1365,1437,642,669]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.01" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="101.0">101 m</quantity>
is a depth outlier that requires re-examination. All other records are from 
<quantity id="887C9B52534EFF80FDF987A5FBC3FD6F" box="[973,1131,678,705]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="m" value="1850.0" valueMax="2700.0" valueMin="1000.0">1000–2700 m</quantity>
.
